name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: I wish the more than 200 athletes on @TeamUSA the best – and I pray they stay safe while they are away from home. 🇺🇸 🇺🇸 🇺🇸

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: The next time a host country is chosen, it is important that the IOC pick any of the dozens of democracies around the world.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text:
The Olympic Committee could have required China to respect the basic liberties athletes enjoy in the United States and other Western countries.
 
But they didn’t.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: This all could have been avoided. We didn’t have to host a unifying event like the Olympics in a country that thinks the book 1984 is an instruction manual.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: The U.S. Olympic & Paralympic Committee has gone as far as to tell American athletes to “assume that every device and every communication, transaction, and online activity will be monitored”, and many other nations have issued similar warnings.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: They had years to plan for these Olympics. But they still chose not to adopt any rules to protect the human rights of Olympians while they are in China. Instead, competitors are required to follow local laws limiting free expression, privacy, and other basic freedoms.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: We shouldn’t pretend that everything is fine in China just because the IOC chose them to host the Olympics.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: If this is how China treats its own people, I think it’s fair to ask: What kind of risks are our athletes facing as they participate in the Olympic Games?

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Her existence was scrubbed from the internet. She disappeared from the public eye for months, and the only appearances she has been allowed to make since have been scripted and supervised by the CCP.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: This wasn’t just any politician: He was the face of China’s successful effort to land the 2022 Olympics. Speaking out about someone like this is dangerous in a country like China. Peng Shuai knew that – but I don’t think she expected what came next.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Last November, one of the most famous athletes in China, tennis star Peng Shuai, posted on social media that a high-ranking politician in the Chinese Communist Party had sexually assaulted her.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: The very same government that’s hosting the Olympics this week is putting innocent people in labor camps and subjecting them to forced sterilization, forced labor, and physical and psychological torture. This is genocide.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: But make no mistake: Beijing 2022 is no ordinary Olympics.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: The American athletes competing in the Olympics this year have earned their spots on Team USA. And I wish them the best as they compete against other athletes from around the world.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text:
I urge my colleagues to think beyond the passions of the moment and do what’s best for our country in the long term.
 
Leave the filibuster in place. Democrats may want to use it again as soon as next year.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text:
Bipartisanship would become a relic of the past.
 
I know Democrats don’t want that to happen. I don’t want it to happen, either.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text:
The truth is that some of my Democratic colleagues want to remake the American system only in their own image, not considering the views of about half of our citizens.

To do that, they have to take an ax to the filibuster.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: When Republicans were in the majority, we said we wouldn’t abolish the legislative filibuster, and we kept our word.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text:
This is not a debate about some arcane Senate rule.
 
This is about protecting the rights of the minority in our democracy.
 
This is about providing stability and certainty to our people.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Democrats were perfectly happy to use the filibuster literally hundreds of times during the four years of the Trump presidency, when the Majority Leader was the Minority Leader and Republicans had even larger majorities in Congress.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: But because the rules don’t allow them to pass their federal takeover of elections or any of their other reckless policies in a 50-50 Senate, many of my Dem colleagues are flip-flopping to oppose the filibuster.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: The first part of that simply isn’t true. The right to vote is not under assault.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Their argument is that lawmakers in red states are trying to make it harder for people to vote, and so it’s necessary for Washington Democrats to take over election administration in all 50 states.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: The American people voted for bipartisanship and compromise in the United States Congress, not a blanket mandate for progressives to reorganize American life as they see fit.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text:
President Biden wants to pass a New Deal. In fact, the reckless spending the president is pushing for dwarfs the New Deal.

Back then the New Deal passed the on the back of Dem supermajorities, but today we have a 50-50 Senate and the Dem majority is razor thin.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Nebraskan Brent Zoucha is a hero, and it is my honor to tell his story. https://t.co/tTRXsgQeIP

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Brent’s mother remembers him as an ideal son who loved his life and everyone around him. We cannot thank him enough for his service to our country.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Brent’s death shocked the central Nebraska community, and during his service, the streets were lined with American Flags and Patriot riders.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: On June 9, 2006, Brent and four other Marines came across an IED. Tragically, all of them lost their lives due to the wounds they sustained.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: His mother remembers talking on the phone with him in early June and sending him a care package of fig cookies. She didn’t know it at the time, but that was the last conversation she would have with him. #NEheroes

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: This area of Iraq saw the majority of its fighting and counterinsurgency from 2004 until 2007. Brent arrived in the heat of battle. #Service

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Coincidentally, he was assigned to the exact Marine Corp unit as his older brother. Once Brent arrived to Twentynine Palms, he and his brother found out that they were both deploying to the AL An Bar Province in Iraq.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: The extreme discipline that his brother and other Marines routinely displayed greatly interested him. So after graduating from @HPCSTORM he enlisted in the @USMC. #NEheroes

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Like many small-town Nebraska boys, Brent spent a lot of time hunting and fishing. He had a special way with animals and even trained a chicken to fly on his shoulder on command.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Brent Zoucha grew up in the small town of Clarks, Nebraska. The youngest of four siblings, his mother described him as having a great smile and always goofing around.

name: Senator Deb Fischer

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: I am honored to tell Cory’s story and join Nebraskans and Americans across our county in saluting Cory’s willingness to serve.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Today, if you go to Chadron, Nebraska you will see the Sergeant Cory Mracek Memorial Post Office. I was proud to work w/ former NE Senator Mike Johanns on a bill renaming this post office in honor Cory.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Communities came together to line the streets as his funeral procession went through their town as it made its 46-mile journey across Nebraska.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: A week later 600 family members, friends, and military officials gathered inside a Nebraska gymnasium to celebrate and honor Cory and his sacrifice for our country.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Cory and two other U.S. service members were killed by the explosion. #NEhero

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: On January 27, 2004, his mother remembers spending the morning instant messaging with Cory to catch up and see how he was doing. Later that same day, Cory and his reconnaissance platoon were performing a mission where they came across an IED.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: After a couple of years in active duty, he was deployed to #Iraq to an area that saw major combat activity and sectarian violence during 2003-2007.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: He came back home in 2001 and transitioned back to the @NENationalGuard. However, when 9/11 happened, Cory told his parents that he was going to go back to the Active Army so he could serve his country. #Service

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: A year later, Cory transferred to the Active Army & was soon deployed to South Korea. He enjoyed his time there and he even participated in the #ManchuaMile where he marched for 24-miles in full combat gear.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: After graduating high school, he went on to attend college at @Chadronstate. While in college he decided to join the @NENationalGuard and left to go train at Fort Sill, Oklahoma. #NEhero

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: During high school, he became involved in many extracurricular activities and played basketball and football.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Born in Chadron, Nebraska, Cory Mracek was always trying to have a good time. He was often found either laughing or trying to make others laugh.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: NOW: I’m continuing my tributes to the men and women who have lost their lives defending our freedom. Please join me in honoring Sergeant Cory Mracek of Hay Springs, NE. https://t.co/hdj9qxTRjg

tweet_text: That means any delay or any error, could put at risk our ability to field an effective nuclear deterrent in the future, and we cannot allow that to happen. In the face of growing threats, our deterrent must remain strong.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Matt was a consistent source of inspiration for his fellow Marines, he was the kind of young man that people were just drawn to. He was tough yet a selfless Marine. #SemperFi

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: For his ultimate sacrifice, Corporal Matt Henderson received the naval achievement medal with cluster, a Purple Heart, and he was the first to receive the prestigious Non-Commissioned Officer Combat Engineer of the Year award posthumously.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Matt warned his squad to get back and take cover but was unable to get out of range himself. The remainder of his squad survived. #Leadership #Service #Sacrifice

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: As a squad leader, Matt was aware of and concerned about the dangers of his second deployment. On May 26, 2004, Matt was leading his squad in sweeping an area in the Al Anbar province of Iraq. During the sweep, Matt and two of his men were killed when an IED was detonated #NEhero

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: In February of 2004, Matt deployed to Iraq for the second time and Jaimie moved back to #Nebraska to be closer to their families.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Upon Matt’s return home in May of 2003, he and Jaimie finally had their big church wedding in Lincoln, NE. They moved to California where Matt was stationed.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: During his deployment, Matt was chosen to be a squad leader due to his #leadership abilities & the respect of the other Marines. Matt’s family had no communication with him during this time and watched the news every evening with the hopes of catching a glimpse of Matt.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: In February of 2003, Matt deployed to Iraq where he joined other U.S. led forces in the invasion of Iraq from Kuwait in order to oust Saddam Hussein. #NEhero

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: On August 4, 2001, Matt proposed to his girlfriend Jaimie on Mission Beach in San Diego just after sunset. As they planned their wedding in Nebraska, Matt’s unit was informed they would be among the first forces to invade Iraq.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Due to his strong interest in the construction field, Matt also finished Combat Engineer School at Camp Lejeune, and he was assigned to the 1st Combat Engineers Battalion at Camp Pendleton.

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: In 2000, Matt joined the @USMC because he was attracted to the discipline & direction it offered. He completed boot camp at @MCRD_SD before attending & completing infantry training at @MCIWPendletonCA. #Service

name: Senator Deb Fischer
tweet_text: Matt loved sports and was a devout @Huskers and @ChicagoBears fan. #GBR #Tradition

name: Senator Deb Fischer

tweet_text: Under current law, the program is a two-year tax credit. This was intended to give Congress the opportunity to determine its effectiveness.
